Part 4

The press meet was held in the Bagbazar courtyard, under the shade of the largest neem tree.

Six plastic chairs.

One table with a green cloth.

Three reporters from the local Bengali dailies, and a photographer who spent ten minutes cleaning his lens with his shirt tail before taking a single shot of the courtyard well.

Sarita sat near the table.

She had returned from Delhi the night before, her walking stick now carrying a small brass cap at the bottom that made a ringing sound against the stone.

Vikram stood near the gate.

A woman was sitting on the second chair, holding a small notepad.

She had grey hair at the temples, her glasses thick, tied to a black cord around her neck.

She was talking to a silver-haired man beside her.

Aftab.

Her husband.

Vikram looked at her.

The shape of the eyelids was the same. The way she held the pen, the tip touching her lower lip as she read her notes.

Ira.

She looked up.

She saw him standing near the gate, his faded cotton shirt dusty from the sweep-work.

She stood up.

She didn't run. She walked slowly, her sandals clicking against the stone tiles he had reset himself.

"Vikram," she said.

"Ira," Vikram said.

Aftab had followed her. He stood beside her, his face quiet, nodding to Vikram with the respectful distance of a husband who had been told a version of a story a long time ago.

"This is Aftab," she said. "We edit the Cuttack weekly now."

"I know," Vikram said.

"I saw the shelter," she said, looking around the courtyard, at Ananya who was writing in the ledger. "It is good work, Vikram. The drivers at the crossing told me about the medicine delivery. They call you Budha Baba."

"They have many names," Vikram said.

He looked at her eyes.

"The cream-colored car," he said. "The one near the press building."

Ira looked down at her notepad.

"I sold it," she said, her voice dropping. "Two weeks after you left it. I used the money to clear my father's bank loan. It was enough to start the Cuttack weekly."

She looked at him again.

"Thank you, Vikram. For leaving it."

"Rohan's office," Vikram said. "The letters you sent."

Ira's brow furrowed.

"Letters? I never sent any letters, Vikram. I haven't spoken to Rohan since 1997."

Vikram felt a small, cold drop of sweat slide down his neck.

"The yellow envelope," he said. "From Cuttack. Rehman."

Ira looked at Aftab.

Aftab looked at Vikram, his eyes going from Vikram's face to the leather bag near the well.

"Rehman?" Ira asked. "Who is Rehman?"

"Your son," Vikram said. "The boy who came to work here."

Ira stared at him.

Not with anger.

With the deep, slow confusion of a journalist who has just realized a source is speaking in a language she doesn't know.

"Vikram," she said, her voice very quiet. "I never had a son."

"Aftab and I... we were married in ninety-eight. We didn't have children."

---

The telephone cabin on the corner of Bagbazar lane smelled of old directories and dry tobacco.

Vikram stood inside.

He dialled the number Rehman had called from.

The number he had written in the ledger margins.

A click.

Then the recorded voice of the exchange, dry and mechanical:

*The number you have dialled does not exist. Please check the directory.*

He dialled again.

The same voice.

He walked back to the shelter.

Ananya was sitting at her table.

"Ananya," Vikram said. "Rehman's canvas bag. The blue one. Where is it?"

"He took it, uncle," she said. "When he went to Alipore."

"The photo," Vikram said. "The one he showed you on his phone. The one of his mother."

Ananya looked at him, her pen stopping over the green ledger.

"He never showed me a photo, uncle."

"He did," Vikram said, his voice rising. "In the kitchen. The day he arrived."

"No, uncle," she said, her eyes large and quiet. "He only had the wooden horse. He said he found it near the well. He never showed a phone. He didn't have a phone."

Vikram walked into the study.

The yellow envelope was sitting on the teak wood desk, near the brass lion paperweight.

He picked it up.

He pulled out the ruled sheets of paper.

The paper was empty.

No Cuttack press details. No handwriting. No story of conversion.

It was a property tax receipt from the municipal corporation, dated March 2015, sent to the *Ahuja Villa* address and forwarded by the clerk.

---

The lawyer, Bannerjee, arrived at six.

He sat on the step of the well, his leather briefcase kept on his knees.

He didn't open it.

"The CEO transfer deed," Vikram said. "Where is it?"

"In my office, Vikram babu," the lawyer said.

"Whose name is on the recipient line?"

Bannerjee looked at the drumstick tree.

"Your name," he said.

"My name?"

"Yes. The power of attorney was drafted in your name. You signed it, but you left the second signature blank. You told me Rehman would sign in Alipore."

"He did sign," Vikram said. "He called me. He said he saw the blue blur."

"Nobody signed, Vikram babu," the lawyer said, his voice dropping. "The papers are still in my briefcase. I went to Alipore. The apartment was registered in the name of *Ummed Trust*, which is a subsidiary of Punarjeevan. The keys were with the security guard."

He looked at Vikram properly now.

"The guard said you rented the flat three years ago. You paid the rent in advance from the Odisha account. Nobody ever lived there, Vikram babu."

"The silver sedan?"

"The sedan was bought by the trust," Bannerjee said. "You bought it yourself in 2018. It has been sitting in the Alipore garage since the day of purchase."

Vikram sat on the stone wall of the well.

The red tea was boiling in the kitchen, the smell of ginger coming through the window.

But the glass on the ledge was empty.

He looked at his hands, at the calluses, at the grey dirt under the nails.

The fourteen hundred crore was in Nandyal.

The seventy-six hundred crore was in Alipore.

But the boy with the blue canvas bag and the rusted zip was nowhere in the city.

He had never been.

[End of Part 4]
